{{Use British English|date=February 2014}} {{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{More citations needed|date=July 2015}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Dumbarton Football Stadium | nickname = The C&G Systems Stadium | image = Strathclyde Homes Stadium - Home Of Dumbarton FC - geograph.org.uk - 2586794.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = The stadium seen from [[Dumbarton Rock]] | pushpin_map = Scotland West Dunbartonshire | pushpin_mapsize = 250 | pushpin_map_caption = Location in West Dunbartonshire | pushpin_label_position = left |coordinates = {{coord|55|56|18.41|N|4|33|41.18|W|type:landmark|display=inline}} | location = [[Dumbarton]], [[West Dunbartonshire]], [[Scotland]] | broke_ground = | opened = 2000 | awards = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Dumbarton F.C.]] | operator = | surface = [[Lawn|Grass]] | construction_cost = | architect = | former_names = * Strathclyde Homes Stadium * Dumbarton Football Stadium Sponsored By DL Cameron * The Bet Butler Stadium * The Cheaper Insurance Direct Stadium * The YOUR Radio 103FM Stadium | tenants = [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]. | seating_capacity = {{SPFL-stadiums|dumbarton}}<ref name="capacity"/><ref>http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/sco/the_rock_stadium_dumbarton</ref> }}
'''The Dumbarton Football Stadium''', commonly known as '''The Rock''', and currently named '''The C&G Systems Stadium''' for sponsorship purposes is a [[stadium]] in [[Dumbarton]], [[Scotland]], used mostly for [[association football|football]] matches; it is the home ground of [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton Football Club]]. The stadium has a capacity of {{SPFL-stadiums|dumbarton}},<ref name="capacity">{{cite web |url=http://spfl.co.uk/clubs/dumbarton/ |title=Dumbarton Football Club|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League |accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> and was built in 2000 after the move away from Dumbarton's former home, [[Boghead Park]]. It was built on part of the site formerly occupied by [[William Denny and Brothers|Denny's shipyard]]. The stadium is 5–10 minutes walk from [[Dumbarton East railway station]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/directions/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219053855/http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/directions/ |archivedate=19 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> on the [[North Clyde Line]]. Dumbarton have the third smallest stadium in the SPFL.
==History== The stadium has just one stand, officially opened on Saturday 2 December 2000 prior to the visit of [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]]; a match which ended 3–0 to the Sons. It is nicknamed The Rock by fans, as it is adjacent to [[Dumbarton Castle]]. Open areas ring the three sides without stands.
The Scotland international team have also used the stadium for training purposes before playing home matches.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dumbarton/8134605.stm Dumbarton investigate new stadium], [[BBC Sport]], 4 July 2009.</ref> [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] have used the stadium for [[UEFA Youth League]] home games.
Aside from football the stadium also hosts many other events; wedding receptions, conferences & various parties are held in the Allied Distillers suite. The ground has also been used for Cruise for Charity, an event which brings together modified car enthusiasts from around Scotland to raise money for charity.
==Names== The original name of the stadium, Strathclyde Homes Stadium, changed after the stadium sponsor, Strathclyde Homes, went into receivership in September 2011.<ref>[http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3654 STADIUM SPONSORSHIP] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418201509/http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3654 |date=18 April 2012 }}, dumbartonfootballclub.com, 12 September 2011.</ref> On 18 February 2012, the stadium was officially renamed Dumbarton Football Stadium, sponsored by DL Cameron.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130121183357/http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3838 STADIUM SPONSORSHIP], dumbartonfootballclub.com, 18 February 2012.</ref> It was renamed again, just five months later on 20 July 2012, The Bet Butler Stadium.<ref>[http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=4059 STADIUM IS RENAMED]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, dumbartonfootballclub.com, 20 July 2012.</ref> On 9 July 2015, the stadium was unveiled as the Cheaper Insurance Direct Stadium, after fan Alex Couper and his company took over the sponsorship.<ref>[https://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=1958 STADIUM SPONSORSHIP], dumbartonfootballclub.com, 10 July 2015.</ref> At the end of the 2016-17 season the name reverted to Dumbarton Football Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Findlay|first1=Alan|title=SPONSORSHIP DEAL ENDS|url=http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3016|website=Dumbarton Football Club|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> In July 2017 the club agreed a deal with local radio station [[Your Radio]], which would see the stadium known as 'The YOUR Radio 103FM Stadium' for at least the next two years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Findlay|first1=Alan|title=SPONSORSHIP NEWS - YOUR RADIO ON BOARD|url=http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3113|website=Dumbarton Football Club|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> That deal was cancelled in May 2018 with Your Radio facing an uncertain future<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3552|title=CLUB STATEMENT - YOUR RADIO|last=|first=|date=1 May 2018|website=Dumbarton Football Club|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=5 May 2018}}</ref>, with C&G Systems agreeing a three year deal a week later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=3588|title=C&G SYSTEMS ARE NEW STADIUM SPONSORS|last=Barrow|first=Simon|date=5 May 2018|website=Dumbarton Football Club|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
